<font color="#FF0000">PATRIOTS </font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan 26  1:15:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I have no guilt for having gone to Vietnam. The weapons aboard the helicopters weren't smart so I had to use care. The targets I hit were soldiers (NVA) or VC shooting at my ship.<br><br>
My only regret is that I lost a great buddy. I guy I knew when we were both kids in the 4th grade. By chance we came together in the same unit some 10 years later. I made it home. He did not. Therein lies my guilt.<br><br>
I survived. I survive today. At times it is a struggle. Had I seen a doctor with the attitude of Dr Spatz when I did sek help to get my head on straight I probably would not have made it this far.<br><br>
To me the only certainty Vietnam did to this country was to bring the majority of us to a point of cynicism that we can no longer function. We can no longer trust our government. We have forgotten we are the government.<br><br>
Until we as a nation can find peace, we will only denigrate the lives given by every soldier that has served. Those lost in battle are the forgotten.<br><br>
The lives lost in future battles will be for naught because we have lost sight of what is right and what is wrong.
<p><code>-- ahernand@manc.edu  (Alex J Hernandez) </code><p>


